04489nam a22005415i 9780773582224DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735822247 a10.1515/97807735822242doi  a(DE-B1597)657777  a(OCoLC)899761670  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDA566.9.G74bM33 2015eb 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a941.0830922231 aMacLaren, Roy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmpire and Ireland :bThe Transatlantic Career of the Canadian Imperialist Hamar Greenwood, 1870–1948 /cRoy MacLaren. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource :b21 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCanadian Origins, 1870–1895 -- tBritish Beginnings, 1895–1906 -- tHouse of Commons, 1906–1910 -- tA Member for the Empire, 1910–1911 -- tPre-War Ambitions, 1911–1914 -- tFirst World War, 1914–1918 -- tPostwar Upheavals, 1918–1920 -- tIreland, 1919–1920 -- tNew Men and New Measures, 1920 -- tA Pussyfoot Chief Secretary, 1920 -- tReprisals and Reprisals, 1920–1921 -- tPeace Feelers, 1920–1921 -- tFinal Manoeuvrings, 1921 -- tTruce, 1921 -- tA Resolution of Sorts, 1921–1922 -- tPostwar Alarms and Excursions, 1922–1924 -- tEgypt and Palestine, 1925 -- tLast Days in the House of Commons, 1925–1930 -- tHouse of Lords and the World of Business, 1930–1948 -- tConclusion -- tBiographical Notes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Empire and Ireland, Roy MacLaren recounts the life and political career of Hamar Greenwood, a young man from rural Canada who reached the imperial pinnacle of the British cabinet. Greenwood’s arduous route was first beset by conservative opposition to his liberal convictions and later by hostility towards his role as chief secretary for Ireland under British prime minister Lloyd George during the tumultuous years of 1920 to 1922. A long-time advocate of Home Rule for Ireland, Greenwood endeavoured to provide Ireland with the same Dominion status as Canada. Dominion Home Rule, however, was not enough for Irish Republicans, who blamed him for the “Black and Tan” reprisals carried out by the British, and too much for Conservative Unionists, who believed he was insufficiently hard line. Eventually abandoning the divided Liberals for the Conservatives, he entered the House of Lords as Viscount Greenwood. By then Britain could no longer sustain an empire which, in his eyes, had been a cradle for justice, liberty, and development. The first biography of Hamar Greenwood, MacLaren’s thought-provoking work also illuminates the meaning of liberal imperialism, a significant factor in political thinking and policy formation throughout the global empire in Greenwood’s time, which still has resonance today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCabinet officerszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aLawyerszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aPoliticianszGreat BritainvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358222440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773582224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773582224/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles